      "evidence": [
        "Asynchronous orchestration in the importer path launches background work (`go configureUploadedPier(...)`) and does not propagate returned failures from the underlying import workflow back to request/observer paths.",
        "Several hot paths mix error handling strategies: some functions return wrapped/specific errors while nearby utility paths log/print and continue with default values, then treat the operation as successful.",
        "Error-to-response mapping is done with string matching (`strings.Contains(err.Error(), \"timed out\")`) rather than typed/canonical error categories, making behavior dependent on caller formatting."
      ],
      "impact_scope": "subsystem",
      "fix_scope": "multi_file_refactor",
      "confidence": "medium"
    }
  },
  "findings": [
    {
      "dimension": "error_consistency",
      "identifier": "ERRC-001",
      "summary": "Importer workflow failures can be dropped because async execution ignores returned errors from upload processing.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/importer/importer.go",
        "goseg/importer/extract.go"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "`HTTPUploadHandler` starts `configureUploadedPier` in a goroutine instead of awaiting the result.",
        "Inside `configureUploadedPier`, `runImportedPierWorkflow` is invoked and its returned error is ignored, so failures are not surfaced to caller-facing status handling."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Run import workflow synchronously and propagate the resulting error to request-level handling, or return errors through a bounded channel with an explicit completion/error path so upload status transitions and failure signals are based on actual workflow outcomes.",
      "confidence": "high",
      "impact_scope": "subsystem",
      "fix_scope": "architectural_change",
      "root_cause_cluster": "async-boundary-error-loss"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "error_consistency",
      "identifier": "ERRC-002",
      "summary": "Timeout handling is determined by string matching on `err.Error()`, creating brittle and non-authoritative error contracts.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/importer/importer.go",
        "goseg/importer/extract.go"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "The importer maps outcomes with a substring check (`strings.Contains(err.Error(), \"timed out")`), then emits a specific status code.",
        "This makes behavior depend on textual formatting rather than typed sentinel/wrapped errors and can silently misclassify unrelated errors that happen to contain that phrase."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Return typed sentinel errors (e.g., `ErrRequestTimeout`) from workflow/execution layers and switch on concrete error values with `errors.Is/As`, keeping message text as diagnostic detail only.",
      "confidence": "high",
      "impact_scope": "module",
      "fix_scope": "multi_file_refactor",
      "root_cause_cluster": "async-boundary-error-loss"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "error_consistency",
      "identifier": "ERRC-003",
      "summary": "Filesystem rewrite path reports success while ignoring writer flush failures.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/system/disk.go",
        "goseg/system/system.go"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "In `CreateGroundSegFilesystem`, writes to the temp mount file use `bufio.Writer` with per-line error checks, but `writer.Flush()` is not checked before success is returned.",
        "In the same area, errors are partially handled during write but final durability errors can be dropped, allowing corrupted or partially written output to be treated as success."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Check and return `writer.Flush()` errors (and defer/validate file close) so failed buffered writes fail the operation instead of being reported as successful.",
      "confidence": "high",
      "impact_scope": "module",
      "fix_scope": "single_edit",
      "root_cause_cluster": "io-error-handling-inconsistency"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "error_consistency",
      "identifier": "ERRC-004",
      "summary": "Core system helper silently downgrades I/O parse errors to a zero-value success result.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/system/system.go",
        "goseg/system/disk.go"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "`GetTemp` logs an error to stdout on read/parse failure and returns `0` instead of returning or propagating an error.",
        "The function exists in a subsystem where similar operations normally report errors, causing callers to interpret a malformed/failed read as a valid temperature reading."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Refactor `GetTemp` to return an error return value and preserve the distinction between real zero-value data and failed reads; update callers to handle that error explicitly.",
      "confidence": "medium",
      "impact_scope": "module",
      "fix_scope": "multi_file_refactor",
      "root_cause_cluster": "io-error-handling-inconsistency"
    }
  ],
  "retrospective": {
    "root_causes": [
      "Error contracts are not consistently propagated across asynchronous and I/O-heavy paths, creating silent failure channels.",
      "String-based error interpretation is used as control flow in places where typed errors should drive behavior."
    ],
    "likely_symptoms": [
      "ERRC-001",
      "ERRC-002",
      "ERRC-004"
    ],
    "possible_false_positives": [
      "Some helper functions may intentionally log-and-continue for best-effort telemetry, though this is not documented and still should be explicit."
    ]
  }
